{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/fighting-financial-fraud-with-artificial-intelligence-f2a6bcaf131e", "time": 1683002589.6934888, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/fighting-financial-fraud-with-artificial-intelligence-f2a6bcaf131e/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Fighting Financial Fraud with Artificial Intelligence | by Roshan Adusumilli | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Fighting Financial Fraud with Artificial Intelligence", "description": "Fraud is a huge problem for businesses; The Association of Certified Fraud Examiners found that the typical organization loses an estimated 5% of its annual revenues to fraud. Worldwide, this\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.kaggle.com/ntnu-testimon/paysim1", "anchor_text": "\u201cSynthetic Financial Dataset\u201d", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://www.kaggle.com/", "anchor_text": "Kaggle", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/1709.05254", "anchor_text": "Detection of Anomalies in Large Scale Accounting Data using Deep Autoencoder Networks", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://becominghuman.ai/artificial-intelligence-and-its-application-in-finance-9f1e0588e777.", "anchor_text": "article", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/roshan-adusumilli-96b104194/", "anchor_text": "Linkedin", "paragraph_index": 9}], "all_paragraphs": ["Fraud is a huge problem for businesses; The Association of Certified Fraud Examiners found that the typical organization loses an estimated 5% of its annual revenues to fraud. Worldwide, this represents an annual loss of $3.7 trillion. Internal and external audits, while often thought of as a pivotal tool for uncovering fraud, are only responsible for 14% and 3% of fraud detection respectively. One of the problems auditors face is finding a metaphorical needle in a haystack: searching for red flags among thousands of legitimate journal entries when less than 1% of them may be deceitful is certainly no easy task. Classifying an extremely small amount of anomalies in a large dataset? Enter autoencoders.", "Autoencoders are a type of neural network that tries to replicate inputs in their outputs. The encoder, a fully connected artificial neural network (ANN), compresses the input data into a latent-space representation (the code). From there, the decoder, also a fully connected ANN, produces the output using only the code. Finally, the reconstruction error measures how the decoder is performing; normal instances will have low reconstruction error while outliers will have high reconstruction errors due to the code. Similar to ANNs, the model trains and gets better over time using backpropagation. From the image above, we can observe that the architecture of the decoder typically mirrors that of the encoder.", "Autoencoders fall under the category of unsupervised learning, meaning they don\u2019t require explicitly labeled data to draw inferences from the training set. Let\u2019s take a more specific look at how autoencoders can be applied in our use case.", "When our autoencoder trains using the \u201cSynthetic Financial Dataset\u201d from Kaggle that contains journal entry attributes, the code for the autoencoder becomes a compressed representation of the input data (of which 99% is normal journal entries). Consequently, the decoder becomes very good at reconstructing normal journal entries. However, anomalies are only a minuscule fraction of the input data, so the decoder yields high reconstruction error when reconstructing journal entries that deviate from the norm. Thus, businesses are alerted to possible instances of fraud.", "The two types of anomalies we will look for are global anomalies and local anomalies. Global accounting anomalies refer to journal entries containing rare attribute values such as odd posting times. Yet, global anomalies can often be attributed to events such as year end adjustments, meaning that the majority of these outliers are false positives. Local accounting anomalies are journal entries showing a rare combination of frequently occurring attribute values. These unusual accounting records are often made by employees intending to mask malicious activity as regular business activity, making them both harder to detect and more likely to point out fraud.", "After our autoencoder programs runs, we see that 80% (56/70) of the global anomalies and 77% (23/30) of the local anomalies which is excellent when you keep in mind that outliers were only 0.018% of the whole dataset. The code for the entire project is attached below.", "Autoencoders can greatly expedite the process of fraud detection. They can comb through the entire list of journal entries and detect anomalies with a solid success rate. Meanwhile, this is an extremely tedious task for auditors who don\u2019t always find evidence of fraud. Although the auditing process isn\u2019t ready to be completely automated, businesses can incorporate autoencoders into their internal controls to reduce the instances of undetected fraud.", "[1] M. Schreyer and T. Sattarov, Detection of Anomalies in Large Scale Accounting Data using Deep Autoencoder Networks (2017), arXiv", "I\u2019m Roshan, a 16 year old passionate about the intersection of artificial intelligence and finance. For a broad view on the applications of AI in finance, check out this article", "Reach out to me on Linkedin", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Ff2a6bcaf131e&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Ffighting-financial-fraud-with-artificial-intelligence-f2a6bcaf131e&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global